WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.339 --> 00:00:05.809
&gt;&gt;(Cliff): Good morning everyone. Figured
we'd do a morning talk today before our inboxes

00:00:05.809 --> 00:00:11.540
get out of control so glad that you're able
to join us this early. The Authors at Google

00:00:11.540 --> 00:00:18.270
program is proud to host Jonathan Spira today.
He's going to discuss an issue very near and

00:00:18.270 --> 00:00:20.830
dear to us, that of information overload.

00:00:20.830 --> 00:00:26.460
Google's mission is of course is to organize
the world's information, but what many of

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:32.780
the public doesn't understand is that we're
also there to make it universally accessible

00:00:32.780 --> 00:00:37.380
and useful. So we're in a constant battle
against information overload; whether it's

00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:43.829
the relevance of our search results, the use
of priority inbox in Gmail, or recent innovations

00:00:43.829 --> 00:00:50.290
like the Google+ Circles as a way of sharing
information among friends.

00:00:50.290 --> 00:00:56.059
So Jonathan Spira today speaks to us about
that in his new book about information overload.

00:00:56.059 --> 00:01:02.530
He is the CEO and Chief Analyst of Basics
which is a thought leader in the world of

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:07.240
information overload and his interests also
extend to photography as well. He co-wrote

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:10.759
a very influential book about the history
of photography.

00:01:10.759 --> 00:01:14.579
Since this book is about information overload
I'll stop my introduction here.

00:01:14.579 --> 00:01:16.779
Please join me in welcoming Jonathan to Google.

00:01:16.779 --> 00:01:17.779
[applause]

00:01:17.779 --> 00:01:23.240
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Spira: Thank you, thank you very
much Cliff. Good morning everyone both here

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:29.259
and in virtual. I'd like to first thank Cliff
very much for inviting me to this.

00:01:29.259 --> 00:01:34.069
This is a topic near and dear to my heart
as I know too many people at Google and many

00:01:34.069 --> 00:01:42.609
people who use Google tools. We think of information
it's kind of too much of a good thing.

00:01:42.609 --> 00:01:47.920
But first, before we start, and both for everyone
here in the room and everyone watching virtually,

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:50.039
how many of you here have Smartphones with
you?

00:01:50.039 --> 00:01:51.340
[pause]

00:01:51.340 --> 00:01:58.959
Everyone almost, no, really? Do you ever use
a Smartphone? Okay cool, that's great. A lot

00:01:58.959 --> 00:02:02.689
of people are tethered to them. Can you just
take them out and show me, I'll hold mine

00:02:02.689 --> 00:02:07.009
up too, if you don't mind and if you're in
virtual land just do the same with us please.

00:02:07.009 --> 00:02:11.329
Sort of like the old TV shows where you used
to connect the dots on the TV screen or something.

00:02:11.329 --> 00:02:13.310
Could you turn them off by the way?

00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:14.310
[laughter]

00:02:14.310 --> 00:02:19.569
Ah, [chuckles] while you have them out just
press that off button. Ah, I do that not because

00:02:19.569 --> 00:02:24.969
I don't want you to get any email or pay attention
to that at all, more it's a question just

00:02:24.969 --> 00:02:26.810
to sort of point out the separation anxiety.

00:02:26.810 --> 00:02:31.760
When I do that in large physical crowds of
people, when a lot of people are not attending

00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:36.230
virtually, if you saw the look of horror on
some people's faces, especially in like really

00:02:36.230 --> 00:02:46.030
uptight business circles, they're like, "What?
You want me to turn this off? To disconnect?"

00:02:46.030 --> 00:02:49.260
The fact that we can disconnect, the fact
that some people don't even have Smartphones

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:54.030
is very refreshing to me. I actually don't
get too much information over my Smartphone,

00:02:54.030 --> 00:02:57.370
in the interest of disclosure I try and keep
that to a minimum.

00:02:57.370 --> 00:03:01.489
But it's interesting when we think of information
one of the earliest ways we kept information

00:03:01.489 --> 00:03:06.780
was on the tablet and it's just kind of ironic
that things haven't really changed very much

00:03:06.780 --> 00:03:13.379
in terms of our use of tablets. I can't figure
it out but we just keep using tablets for

00:03:13.379 --> 00:03:14.379
information.

00:03:14.379 --> 00:03:19.400
Before I really get in to this though, I did
bring a few friends of mine along to talk

00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:23.489
about the problem of information overload.
So if you can listen to them for just a moment

00:03:23.489 --> 00:03:24.489
I'd appreciate it.

00:03:24.489 --> 00:03:27.120
&gt;&gt;Larry Bowen: Information overload basically
slows me down because I'm interacting with

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:28.580
information that's irrelevant, out of context.

00:03:28.580 --> 00:03:33.489
&gt;&gt;Peter Miles: [inaudible] the reality today
is that it comes at you at such a high volume

00:03:33.489 --> 00:03:42.530
you have to learn very quickly how to prioritize
that information and filter out what's useful

00:03:42.530 --> 00:03:44.790
and what's not useful.

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:51.379
&gt;&gt;Max Christoff: I feel my pulse quickening
I'm so engrossed in trying to deal with the

00:03:51.379 --> 00:03:55.109
emails that are coming in, the instant messages
that are popping up on the screen, the phone

00:03:55.109 --> 00:04:02.129
calls coming in simultaneously. It's not a
good feeling.

00:04:02.129 --> 00:04:05.310
&gt;&gt;Matt Brezina: Sometimes it gets a little
frustrating. If I don't check it I almost

00:04:05.310 --> 00:04:08.120
feel like something's missing in my life.
If I'm sitting with no TV on, no iPhone in

00:04:08.120 --> 00:04:10.439
my hand, and no computer in front of me I
kind of feel lonely.

00:04:10.439 --> 00:04:14.189
&gt;&gt;Andy Chew: There's no question that the
amount of information I receive makes it harder

00:04:14.189 --> 00:04:15.650
for me to prioritize.

00:04:15.650 --> 00:04:19.280
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Spira: Well, as you can see a lot
of these people are completely broken up about

00:04:19.280 --> 00:04:23.210
the problem. So I never saw that happen before
but.

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:28.530
I wanna cover a couple of things and I also
want to invite you to ask any questions as

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:34.099
we go along. I am imminently interruptible,
I don't mind interruptions, in fact I'd love

00:04:34.099 --> 00:04:39.560
to hear questions so we are sort of contextual
in where ever I am. Just stop me please, if

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:41.830
I don't see you just jump up a little warn
and stop me.

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:47.750
I'm gonna cover some changes in how we work,
how we look at information overload, what

00:04:47.750 --> 00:04:48.920
it is, and what we can do.

00:04:48.920 --> 00:04:54.840
One of the problems that I noticed, and just
by background, I've been researching the problem

00:04:54.840 --> 00:05:00.819
of information overload indirectly for over
20 years; I've been studying how people work,

00:05:00.819 --> 00:05:06.250
how people collaborate, share information,
what people do with information, and you won't

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:10.660
be surprised to know that there's problems,
there's things that get in the way.

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:17.110
And ultimately after studying and interviewing
people and watching how people work we found

00:05:17.110 --> 00:05:23.340
that information overload, and this goes back
15 years, was a significant problem. At the

00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:30.069
time, however, everyone was so giddy about
the fact that we had email. It was just so

00:05:30.069 --> 00:05:35.440
easy to cc a couple of thousand extra colleagues.
It was just so easy to share content and push

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:42.220
it out to so many people that it really didn't
matter. Nobody thought it was a significant

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:45.430
problem. People actually thought I was kind
of nuts for bringing it up because, "Oh no,

00:05:45.430 --> 00:05:49.849
don't be silly. Just go back to your corner
do some more research. We have email. It's

00:05:49.849 --> 00:05:55.789
great, it's amazing, we can email the world."
The ramifications of adding a few thousand

00:05:55.789 --> 00:05:58.050
extra people just weren't clear to them.

00:05:58.050 --> 00:06:02.300
And the way we view the workplace, a lot of
people still have this sort of romantic and

00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:07.780
somewhat black and white notion of what the
workplace and what the workforce really is.

00:06:07.780 --> 00:06:15.740
If you go back at the turn of the last century
90% of the workforce was manual and largely

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:20.370
agrarian in nature. That's a huge change from
today where plurality of the workforce is

00:06:20.370 --> 00:06:26.520
comprised of knowledge workers, such as ourselves.
Today, in fact, you have to really look for

00:06:26.520 --> 00:06:28.259
a manual workforce and it's about 20%. Yes?

00:06:28.259 --> 00:06:31.110
&gt;&gt;Female #1: Sorry is that in U.S. or is that
international?

00:06:31.110 --> 00:06:36.259
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Spira: These figures, almost all
the figures I will cite today are U.S. If

00:06:36.259 --> 00:06:42.520
I go out of a U.S. figure I will explicitly
identify it as non-U.S. or worldwide or AMIA.

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:46.729
But thank you for mentioning that yes. As
of right now, I mean there's just so much

00:06:46.729 --> 00:06:52.930
stuff we had in the U.S. that I tend to stay
with that and a lot of the data we need which

00:06:52.930 --> 00:06:56.800
I'll get into a little later, like Bureau
of Labor Statistics and Census just isn't

00:06:56.800 --> 00:06:58.909
as easily available worldwide.

00:06:58.909 --> 00:07:04.580
Today as I mentioned knowledge workers are
the plurality of the workforce and that's

00:07:04.580 --> 00:07:09.229
even the start contrast to 25 years ago where
a majority of the workforce was comprised

00:07:09.229 --> 00:07:15.069
of industrial workers. And we saw the rise
of information workers and information professionals,

00:07:15.069 --> 00:07:20.870
and this was foreshadowed in the cinema. One
of my favorite movies relating to this I don't

00:07:20.870 --> 00:07:23.470
know, how many people here are familiar with
the movie Desk Set?

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:24.490
[pause]

00:07:24.490 --> 00:07:32.509
Okay, 2%, no. [laughs] Spencer Tracy, Katherine
Hepburn, and the movie if you haven't seen

00:07:32.509 --> 00:07:37.850
it, it's actually very relevant to what I'm
presuming most of us do. Spencer Tracy is

00:07:37.850 --> 00:07:44.210
a computer salesman for a very large technology
company and he is selling and installing,

00:07:44.210 --> 00:07:48.159
it's amazing he can do everything in this
film; he's selling and installing a large

00:07:48.159 --> 00:07:55.740
mainframe. You remember those, that will run
a television network where Katherine Hepburn

00:07:55.740 --> 00:08:00.909
who, just to show you it was 1950's, she was
the chief librarian and her name was Bunny.

00:08:00.909 --> 00:08:05.960
You wouldn't quite see that happening in film
today; it's kinda, just wouldn't go over as

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:06.960
well.

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:11.280
But anyway and they end up with a challenge
and the challenge, and I think this is particularly

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:17.580
relevant at Google, is to answer a question.
Now if you think about it today we still go

00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:23.009
to a search box, we type in a search query,
we get search results, sometimes depending

00:08:23.009 --> 00:08:27.689
on how well we do it, and most people don't
know really how to use the tools, you get

00:08:27.689 --> 00:08:32.970
564,768 results, that's probably a typical
number although I'm sure you guys could tell

00:08:32.970 --> 00:08:35.030
me a more typical average number.

00:08:35.030 --> 00:08:42.010
And the question that they posed, the challenge
question as they say on some shows in television

00:08:42.010 --> 00:08:48.810
today, was what kind of car did the King of
the Watusis drive? It's not gonna give away

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:53.430
anything in the movie to say that the mainframe
didn't do terribly well in answering this

00:08:53.430 --> 00:09:00.110
and of course Bunny and her team of librarians
did. I promise that was not a spoiler.

00:09:00.110 --> 00:09:05.200
But it's interesting today if you go to Google
or any other tool and you just ask the same

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:08.330
question you're not gonna get an answer but
you'll get referred back to the movie.

00:09:08.330 --> 00:09:09.330
[laughter]

00:09:09.330 --> 00:09:14.900
[laughs] So you still don't know that he drove
a specially designed Pontiac, for those of

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:20.250
you who remember the late, lamented Pontiac
brand. I've always found that's a very interesting

00:09:20.250 --> 00:09:21.250
example.

00:09:21.250 --> 00:09:28.500
Now going back to how we work, as you can
see the figure that's going up, that is abstract

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:34.410
tasks. Routine tasks you can see are heading
down and declining and manual tasks which

00:09:34.410 --> 00:09:39.180
declined dramatically through 1990 seem to
have plateaued and continue at that sort of

00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:44.540
low level. So there's a tremendous amount
of change in just the way we look at jobs

00:09:44.540 --> 00:09:45.540
and tasks.

00:09:45.540 --> 00:09:49.090
I mentioned already that knowledge workers
comprise a plurality of the workforce. One

00:09:49.090 --> 00:09:53.560
of the things we found out when we surveyed
Global 2000 companies, again this probably

00:09:53.560 --> 00:09:58.390
won't be surprising to you, is that 80% of
the companies we talked to in pretty much

00:09:58.390 --> 00:10:02.680
all the Global 2000 were simply not prepared
for the types of changes we're talking about.

00:10:02.680 --> 00:10:07.750
Now what do I mean by not prepared? It's not
as if they're not using technology, they most

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:11.920
certainly are using technology, but they're
using a lot of technology, something I refer

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:17.950
to as technology sprawl which is kind of like
urban sprawl. And they have so much technology

00:10:17.950 --> 00:10:22.260
[coughs] that they simply get in trouble because
they don't really know which system they're

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:24.440
using when and for what and so on.

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:30.340
So you end up with a lot of fun things happening
like somebody uses one content management

00:10:30.340 --> 00:10:34.120
system to create something and then of course
we say, "Don't use Google for search," they

00:10:34.120 --> 00:10:40.330
can't find stuff. And then somebody else recreates
the entire project because they couldn't find

00:10:40.330 --> 00:10:44.830
it and they didn't know it was in the content
management system number 33.

00:10:44.830 --> 00:10:52.440
I know content management is not a main thing
at Google but if you had a group of a thousand

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:55.880
employees, how many content management systems
do you think would be reasonable for this

00:10:55.880 --> 00:10:59.460
like small group of a thousand employees?
What's a reasonable number?

00:10:59.460 --> 00:11:00.460
[pause]

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:01.460
Anyone?

00:11:01.460 --> 00:11:02.460
&gt;&gt;Male #1: One.

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:09.200
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Spira: One, yeah one would be actually
what I would think of, yeah one. How 'bout

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:10.200
97? [chuckles]

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:15.670
We were talking to a group at a, I'll just
say a large semiconductor company, and we

00:11:15.670 --> 00:11:21.250
were helping them with, we were incorporating
some of their stuff into our research and

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:27.000
we happened to do a little inventory and they
were as shocked as I was, 97. That's a lot.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:32.580
It's like for every 100 employees we basically
have a content management platform. Just can't

00:11:32.580 --> 00:11:33.940
imagine how they find things.

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:39.860
So today especially with the change in where
we work and the type of work we do, with 40%

00:11:39.860 --> 00:11:44.790
of the workforce working regularly, meaning
two or more times a week in non-traditional,

00:11:44.790 --> 00:11:48.750
non-diverting environments, there's a lot
of change underfoot.

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:54.760
And we have the rise of the knowledge worker,
the knowledge worker, us again. I just wanna

00:11:54.760 --> 00:11:59.020
throw out a definition from the book. The
easy definition is what a knowledge worker

00:11:59.020 --> 00:12:02.870
is. I just say a knowledge worker is a participant
in the knowledge economy.

00:12:02.870 --> 00:12:07.020
Then of course I have to define the knowledge
economy which is an economic environment where

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:12.520
information and its manipulation are the commodity.
And that's really dramatic contrast to the

00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:15.240
industrial economy where you have raw goods.

00:12:15.240 --> 00:12:20.380
Now, keep in mind at the end of the day a
lot of companies still build refrigerators,

00:12:20.380 --> 00:12:26.780
automobiles, washing machines, and so on.
They build things, but the amount of information

00:12:26.780 --> 00:12:32.070
intensive work that even goes into the creation
of these things and also into the manufacture,

00:12:32.070 --> 00:12:33.070
think of robotics.

00:12:33.070 --> 00:12:38.020
I don't know if anyone has toured a car factory
recently? if you go do the BMW tour either

00:12:38.020 --> 00:12:44.170
at Munich or Spartanburg, or Leipzig you see
all these robots which in German they say,

00:12:44.170 --> 00:12:47.580
"roborts" and people get confused about the
Roberts who are doing all the work here --

00:12:47.580 --> 00:12:48.900
[laughter]

00:12:48.900 --> 00:12:53.370
and they're doing all this stuff, it's like
a ballet carefully choreographed. So they

00:12:53.370 --> 00:12:57.290
have to be controlled and managed so the people
on the floor who are managing them are knowledge

00:12:57.290 --> 00:12:58.720
workers as well.

00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:05.110
Knowledge workers, as you here at Google know,
we own our means of production. If we leave

00:13:05.110 --> 00:13:11.430
and we don't come back the next day or check
in the next day or the next week we've taken

00:13:11.430 --> 00:13:15.981
our means of production with us and with that
a lot of valuable information. A lot of our

00:13:15.981 --> 00:13:21.000
knowledge work isn't tied to a specific location,
that's the beauty of the whole thing especially

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.970
when you have a beautiful campus like you
do, you can work almost anywhere.

00:13:24.970 --> 00:13:31.420
And knowledge workers, especially people coming
into the workforce now have very, very different

00:13:31.420 --> 00:13:34.541
and widely diverging expectations about how
to work.

00:13:34.541 --> 00:13:38.200
And here's some typical knowledge workers
throughout the ages. It was very hard to get

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:42.590
the picture of the early knowledge workers
I should just add because they were not commonly

00:13:42.590 --> 00:13:44.890
referred to as knowledge workers at the time
of course.

00:13:44.890 --> 00:13:50.080
So what do knowledge workers do? Number one,
not a big surprise, they search. People are

00:13:50.080 --> 00:13:54.250
constantly searching for things, most of the
time as we know they don't find things. There's

00:13:54.250 --> 00:14:00.840
an oft cited stat that 50% of all searches
fail. I'd be interested actually to hear any

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:05.350
thoughts from the Google point of view in
general because this is a very, very, general,

00:14:05.350 --> 00:14:09.810
overall statistic relating to corporate search
and all sorts of search.

00:14:09.810 --> 00:14:21.000
But we found that 50% of the searches people
think succeeded actually failed and they don't

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:27.500
realize it. So what happens is they use the
result, the answer, again this is somewhat

00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:31.710
problematic and I'm hoping that someone here,
I'm sure people are working on more natural

00:14:31.710 --> 00:14:36.050
language search 'cause we like to actually
get into a question and actually get an answer

00:14:36.050 --> 00:14:43.990
or several answer type of environment ultimately
to move away from 564,000 search results.

00:14:43.990 --> 00:14:49.290
But if you use stuff that comes out of the
search where it's not the right thing, it's

00:14:49.290 --> 00:14:53.760
not the best information and you don't realize
it's the old thing or of course the fact that

00:14:53.760 --> 00:14:58.310
any clever 14 year old can create his own
website and it's really sometimes hard to

00:14:58.310 --> 00:15:04.290
tell the difference between that and a well
establish site, you may end up using the wrong

00:15:04.290 --> 00:15:05.290
information.

00:15:05.290 --> 00:15:09.400
Now people, knowledge workers, spend a lot
of time creating, a lot of time as I mentioned

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:14.520
before recreating when you can't find stuff
because somebody put the very important document

00:15:14.520 --> 00:15:19.440
in content management system 33 and you didn't
know that 33 existed, you didn't even know

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:24.920
your organization had 97 content management
systems. [chuckles] Just thinking about that

00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:27.940
number is just mind boggling. You recreate
it.

00:15:27.940 --> 00:15:33.070
Now recreating can be actually a very time
intensive thing because you form a team or

00:15:33.070 --> 00:15:37.930
an ad hoc team, people spend lots of time
reinventing the wheel and doing what somebody

00:15:37.930 --> 00:15:43.120
six months ago or three months ago already
did and never the twain shall meet. We spend

00:15:43.120 --> 00:15:47.080
a lot of time communicating and we spend a
lot of time sharing information networking.

00:15:47.080 --> 00:15:55.460
Now this is a chart with our stats that ran
in the Times about two years ago and it's

00:15:55.460 --> 00:16:00.800
been updated since but I'm showing you this
not because it's old and obsolete because

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:07.170
one key number changed dramatically, the last
figure. Knowledge workers by and large think

00:16:07.170 --> 00:16:11.250
for a living; we reflect, we think, that's
what I think we're supposed to be doing.

00:16:11.250 --> 00:16:16.530
According to the stats we came up with a few
years ago we found that by the end of the

00:16:16.530 --> 00:16:23.820
day after everything that's spent in the day
we have 12% left. Well I'm sorry to say I

00:16:23.820 --> 00:16:31.390
was wrong; 12 percent was wildly optimistic.
When we redid the study and we used a larger

00:16:31.390 --> 00:16:36.981
group and we refined our questions we found
out that at the end of the day 5% of the day

