[chuckles], this is from Marsh &amp; McLennan

00:34:08.200 --> 00:34:12.950
which is a large company in the insurance
field. Anybody wanna guess, and these people

00:34:12.950 --> 00:34:19.040
own the to field, it's not the cc or bcc field,
I just wanna, and by the way on average five

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:24.190
emails like this per day went out. Anybody
wanna guess how many people are in the to

00:34:24.190 --> 00:34:28.850
field here? We gave this to an intern to count.

00:34:28.850 --> 00:34:29.850
[laughter]

00:34:29.850 --> 00:34:34.669
[laughs] That's what interns are for. Sorry
if there are any in the room.

00:34:34.669 --> 00:34:43.340
There's 5,000 people in the to field and this
was a very typical letter email that people

00:34:43.340 --> 00:34:47.179
at Marsh would send out saying, "Hey, does
anybody know anybody at this company?" It

00:34:47.179 --> 00:34:51.380
was called an all hands, it even had a name
it was called an all hands email and that

00:34:51.380 --> 00:34:55.610
was a huge challenge because they would get
all these and of course what happened? Somebody

00:34:55.610 --> 00:34:59.830
hits reply to all, to all 5,000 says, "No,
sorry, I don't." And then of course somebody

00:34:59.830 --> 00:35:04.260
else hits reply to all saying, "Take me off
this list," things like that. Does that sound

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:05.260
familiar?

00:35:05.260 --> 00:35:10.570
There was a meltdown actually Colonel Marksteiner
had told me about this great email meltdown

00:35:10.570 --> 00:35:14.900
at Maxwell Air Force Base where he was attending
a conference with some really big brass, the

00:35:14.900 --> 00:35:16.760
generals with the stripes and all that.

00:35:16.760 --> 00:35:22.590
And when you go into a secure briefing room
you have to leave your Smartphone behind and

00:35:22.590 --> 00:35:26.680
while they were in this briefing on the threat
from Russia and China and all that, really

00:35:26.680 --> 00:35:34.290
high level information warfare stuff, somebody,
a clerk at Maxwell Air Force Base sent out

00:35:34.290 --> 00:35:40.520
this little email about some sort of Bunco
card game or something like that and she accidentally

00:35:40.520 --> 00:35:46.760
sent it to two bases, so it was about 50,000
people on the total mailing list.

00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:51.630
Of course everybody hit reply to all, some
people commented, some people said, "Take

00:35:51.630 --> 00:35:57.080
me off this God damned list," and things like
that. And by the time all the big brass got

00:35:57.080 --> 00:36:02.320
out of the meeting, they went; they turned
their Smartphones back on and there was no

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:04.450
email.

00:36:04.450 --> 00:36:08.470
While they were discussing this huge threat
from China, Russia, where ever the threat

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:15.350
is may be coming from [chuckles] this little
email about a Bunco card game completely brought

00:36:15.350 --> 00:36:21.430
down the Air Force base, two bases actually.
So it's really interesting to see what can

00:36:21.430 --> 00:36:22.430
happen.

00:36:22.430 --> 00:36:28.710
I've been sort of giving tips a little bit,
which here may be preaching to the choir,

00:36:28.710 --> 00:36:33.360
but I do tell people to read what people send
you and to read what you send. I get so many

00:36:33.360 --> 00:36:37.780
emails where clearly the person just hasn't
read anything of what they put into the email

00:36:37.780 --> 00:36:39.100
and it makes no sense.

00:36:39.100 --> 00:36:44.590
I really try to practice what I preach and
read what I'm about to send someone, I try

00:36:44.590 --> 00:36:50.140
and have some degree of empathy for people.
I try to use a variety of search tools, I

00:36:50.140 --> 00:36:55.760
try to use arguments in my search, again I'm
at Google, you guys know this way better than

00:36:55.760 --> 00:36:59.930
I do. And I try to do little things like I
keep my instant message status updated and

00:36:59.930 --> 00:37:00.930
stuff like that.

00:37:00.930 --> 00:37:03.040
I did wanna share a couple of things.

00:37:03.040 --> 00:37:09.520
Some really interesting things from the surveys
that we do where people tell us how they remain

00:37:09.520 --> 00:37:15.680
focused, obvious things like headphones, those
are pretty easy. I like the people who take

00:37:15.680 --> 00:37:20.440
laptops and hide somewhere. One person talked
about going to the conference room, turning

00:37:20.440 --> 00:37:24.501
the lights off, drawing the curtains, and
actually sitting under the conference room

00:37:24.501 --> 00:37:25.501
table.

00:37:25.501 --> 00:37:26.501
[laughter]

00:37:26.501 --> 00:37:31.940
Somebody else talked about going to cafes
and Starbucks across town so nobody would

00:37:31.940 --> 00:37:36.240
know them and then they were able to get work
done. But I really like the guy who turns

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:41.920
grumpy to the point of where no one will actually
talk to him until he's finished. I mean that's

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:48.500
just, "Get away from me." That'll get people
to leave you alone right? And stuff like that.

