00:41:44.190 --> 00:41:45.190
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Okay.

00:41:45.190 --> 00:41:46.190
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Spira: so I don't --

00:41:46.190 --> 00:41:47.190
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Sure.

00:41:47.190 --> 00:41:48.190
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Spira: but the short answer --

00:41:48.190 --> 00:41:49.190
&gt;&gt;Female #2: They won't be bored 'cause they
--

00:41:49.190 --> 00:41:50.190
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Spira: Okay.

00:41:50.190 --> 00:41:51.190
&gt;&gt;Female #2: get a lot of emails from us.
[laughs]

00:41:51.190 --> 00:41:53.980
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Spira: The short answer or the
medium answer is basically it's a very tough

00:41:53.980 --> 00:41:58.690
question and it's a question of fine tuning
to your audience.

00:41:58.690 --> 00:42:03.270
I'll give you an example: I had a conversation
with Jim O'Donnell who's the CEO of BMW of

00:42:03.270 --> 00:42:07.870
North America and we were talking, this was
at a cocktail party, and he said, "Oh yeah

00:42:07.870 --> 00:42:14.470
information overload, I had somebody print
out everything we send to our dealerships

00:42:14.470 --> 00:42:18.600
and it was so and so many feet every week
of communication."

00:42:18.600 --> 00:42:23.740
Now I had never thought until Jim mentioned
this of measuring information overload by

00:42:23.740 --> 00:42:29.420
feet. I thought that was a great idea I said,
"Jim this is brilliant. I've never measured

00:42:29.420 --> 00:42:33.540
how many feet or yards or meters information
overload could be." And he said, "Yeah, we

00:42:33.540 --> 00:42:39.750
had like," I think he said seven feet or something,
and this is paper, printed, vertically stacked.

00:42:39.750 --> 00:42:45.040
No one could digest, no one in a dealership
or anywhere, no human could digest all of

00:42:45.040 --> 00:42:49.710
this information. So he said, "We have to
figure out something to figure out whom to

00:42:49.710 --> 00:42:55.110
get the information to and via what modality
and what has to be pushed versus what has

00:42:55.110 --> 00:42:56.570
to be pulled."

00:42:56.570 --> 00:43:02.191
And I'm using that as an example because it's
a different type of problem but it's a very

00:43:02.191 --> 00:43:09.200
similar problem at the same time. It's just,
it shows that you really have to think of

00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:14.440
your audience and understand and then develop
strategies to not necessarily put everything

00:43:14.440 --> 00:43:20.411
in front of someone's nose as opposed to just
making it available and hoping, but you can't

00:43:20.411 --> 00:43:22.470
just have things where you hope somebody'll
know.

00:43:22.470 --> 00:43:27.850
I mean that gets into the urgent and important
thing as well. I think the key thing here

00:43:27.850 --> 00:43:33.770
is that we've lost our ability to understand
urgent, important, and all that. And until

00:43:33.770 --> 00:43:39.770
we regain that balance, that gleichgewicht
in German, the sense of balance that keeps

00:43:39.770 --> 00:43:47.100
us from going crazy, it's going to be a very
difficult challenge in corporate communications

00:43:47.100 --> 00:43:48.700
and also external communications.

00:43:48.700 --> 00:43:53.470
People who have to communicate massive amounts
of information about products, technology,

00:43:53.470 --> 00:44:01.170
services, the government I mean there's, everything,
there's just so much you have to figure out

00:44:01.170 --> 00:44:04.900
and nobody does it, you're never gonna satisfy
the audience.

00:44:04.900 --> 00:44:09.080
I think you have to recognize that from the
beginning no matter what you're never gonna

00:44:09.080 --> 00:44:14.610
get 100% satisfaction from your audience,
but you may find better ways especially by

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:19.930
going and polling your audience, by giving
choices.

00:44:19.930 --> 00:44:24.260
And I would conclude my answer, which is actually
more long winded than I thought it would be,

00:44:24.260 --> 00:44:29.940
by trying to develop multiple modalities so
that each person can actually choose how he

00:44:29.940 --> 00:44:34.470
or she wants to receive information.

00:44:34.470 --> 00:44:42.390
I always use the example one person's junk
mail is another person's L.L. Bean catalog.

00:44:42.390 --> 00:44:46.000
If you don't care about L.L. Bean and you
don't want the boots, you're not really gonna

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:50.410
be happy that the catalog came. However if
you like L.L. Bean you're gonna be like, "Oh

00:44:50.410 --> 00:44:54.600
great! I just needed to order something and
the catalog came," or "I got an email from

00:44:54.600 --> 00:44:56.080
them," or something like that.

00:44:56.080 --> 00:45:01.190
So it's really a question of perspective,
but I'd say the ability to give people a choice,

00:45:01.190 --> 00:45:04.250
and again I'm happy to talk to you more about
this after and share some of our research

00:45:04.250 --> 00:45:10.480
that looks at this in more even what Jim O'Donnell
said. But it's a matter of choice, giving

00:45:10.480 --> 00:45:11.840
people choice.

