00:45:16.350 --> 00:45:20.460
&gt;&gt;Male #4: I'll wrap up with a final question
then. So first of all thank you for coming,

00:45:20.460 --> 00:45:26.040
we have a lot of GTD acolytes here that believe
in getting things done and so we really believe

00:45:26.040 --> 00:45:27.040
in that technique.

00:45:27.040 --> 00:45:31.760
But I wanted to go back to your question on
the difference between urgent and important

00:45:31.760 --> 00:45:38.030
and the issue seems like a cultural one, one
you can't really solve by sending out an email

00:45:38.030 --> 00:45:40.620
about what people should consider as urgent
and important.

00:45:40.620 --> 00:45:47.330
So how have organizations tackled this and
basically made people aware of conflicting

00:45:47.330 --> 00:45:51.120
priorities that are not within their own window,
that other people are working on important

00:45:51.120 --> 00:45:52.120
things too?

00:45:52.120 --> 00:45:55.360
&gt;&gt;Jonathan Spira: Well one of the things I've
recommended to people in terms of getting

00:45:55.360 --> 00:46:00.860
the question of urgent versus important across
and it is a very, very tricky question and

00:46:00.860 --> 00:46:07.810
it is cultural, generational, educational.
There are lots of things that come up in this,

00:46:07.810 --> 00:46:12.810
is basically to put it all out on the table;
to give people an opportunity to say, to have

00:46:12.810 --> 00:46:16.360
a discussion and to make, within work groups
in particular.

00:46:16.360 --> 00:46:22.500
I think it actually is more pertinent in small
groups than on large organizational charts,

00:46:22.500 --> 00:46:27.180
to make it clear, especially if you if you
start to see a problem crop up, that there

00:46:27.180 --> 00:46:33.590
are way too many urgent and important requests
and that not everything, because I would say

00:46:33.590 --> 00:46:38.290
if anything close to 80% of what people tend
to believe their doing is urgent and important

00:46:38.290 --> 00:46:43.620
at the same time, is really to put this into
perspective.

00:46:43.620 --> 00:46:51.320
If you can, if a manager within a work group
can have a dialog that establishes a protocol

00:46:51.320 --> 00:46:58.410
and brings people into thinking about it,
again raising even the topic because people

00:46:58.410 --> 00:47:03.130
are blithely unaware this is a problem to
being with. It's not as if people do this

00:47:03.130 --> 00:47:12.400
deliberately, there's no design here. It's
more a question of it's a lack of awareness.

00:47:12.400 --> 00:47:18.300
And just like with information overload I
know from what we've done when we've talked

00:47:18.300 --> 00:47:24.631
to large corporations we know that just simply
raising a few facts about information overload,

00:47:24.631 --> 00:47:29.660
some of the facts I've covered here, tends
to actually bring down the incidents of information

00:47:29.660 --> 00:47:31.330
overload by 10 to 15%.

00:47:31.330 --> 00:47:35.300
It's not a technology problem in fact I should
have said this earlier. I don't see information

00:47:35.300 --> 00:47:42.160
overload today as a technology problem nor
do I see a lot of the solutions as being technology

00:47:42.160 --> 00:47:43.160
based now.

00:47:43.160 --> 00:47:47.940
I think that there are future things that
can be solved by technology but ultimately

00:47:47.940 --> 00:47:53.021
I think that what we're really after is raising
awareness so we understand it's a very, very

00:47:53.021 --> 00:47:58.680
human problem. It goes to core human frailties
and if we're able to address those I think

00:47:58.680 --> 00:48:05.100
then we have a much greater likelihood of
being able to lower the overall incidents

00:48:05.100 --> 00:48:10.450
of information overload and restore what really
we've decimated in the work life balance,

00:48:10.450 --> 00:48:15.691
bring some time back both for us personally
as well as some productivity to the workplace.

00:48:15.691 --> 00:48:20.390
And I think we'll all be just happier, more
relaxed, and more chill at the end of the

00:48:20.390 --> 00:48:21.760
day. So that's really it.

